com.inqwell.any

Class AnyFormat

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.text.Format
      • com.inqwell.any.AnyFormat
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Any, Composite, Map, Serializable, Cloneable

    public class AnyFormat
extends Format
implements Map, Cloneable
    This class acts as a container for the various standard Java concrete formatting classes, as well as itself being a formatter. This allows us to extend the standard formatting capabilities of the java.text package to Any implementations.

    Formatting directives are supported. These directives apply some additional functionality to the formatting operation. A formatting directive has the syntax name=value. There may be any number of these, each separated with the "@" character and the directives as a whole must appear as a contiguous string, itself bounded "@" characters. Currently, the only supported directive is the zone directive. This directive controls the TimeZone used to format instances. If absent, an is formatted according to the default time zone for the JVM. Otherwise, the specified time zone is used. As an example: 

    
   "dd MMM yyyy HH:mm@zone='America/New_York'@"
    will always format the date/time against the New York time zone.

    All directive values are either quoted strings (as above) or, if not quoted, taken as node paths. These paths can be resolved against a given root when resolveDirectives is called. The result must be a value suitable for the directive. In the case of zone this means a string whose value is a valid time zone ID.

    There are convenience methods to make the appropriate format object for the type of Any. Note that while a formatter for DateI will not do for formatting AnyInt, any kind of formatter can be passed an AnyString and the width and justification settings will be honoured. This is useful for formatting column headings in report generators with the same attributes as the column data, regardless of the type of that data.

      • hasIdentity

        public boolean hasIdentity()
        Description copied from interface: Composite
        Determine whether a Composite instance is a managed object. Being managed means that hashCode() and equals() operate on the object instance itself rather than the instance's members. This means that the instance can be tracked where it is important to ensure that multiple threads are dealing with physically the same object.

        Most Composite implementations will return false with identity semantics being bestowed by suitable decorator. Note that
